Hillary Clinton and Bernie Sanders go into the Tuesday nominating contests with equal numbers of pledged delegates; yet the Southern states that dominate the contest and award the greatest number of delegates more closely mirror the electorate of Nevada and South Carolina, states Clinton won decisively. With Clinton expected to repeat her strong showing among minority voters in Southern states, Sanders would need to win large margins over Clinton in Minnesota, Massachusetts, Colorado, and Oklahoma, in addition to his home states of Vermont, where he is predicted to do well. The larger states show the two in a close race, and it would be unlikely for Sanders to pull the wide lead in each needed to catch up with what is expected to be Clinton's wide margins across the south. However, Sanders strong organization resulted in a closer than expected showing in the Nevada caucus, and the caucus system could play to Sanders' advantage in those states. Current delegate count: Clinton 91, Sanders 65 Super Tuesday states and delegate number: AL 20, AR 37, CO 78, GA 117, MA 116, MN 93, OK 42, TN 75, TX 251, VT 26, VA 109 (Source: https://ballotpedia.org/2016_presidential_nominations:_calendar_and_delegate_rules) Democratic primary rules are stupidly complicated (probably worse than the Republican rules, so I'm oversimplifying and assigning delegates proportionally to 538's projected results for the states they have listed (polls-plus), which include AR, GA, MA, OK, TN, TX, VT, VA (http://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/election-2016/primary-forecast/virginia-republican/) Clinton: AR 24, GA 82, MA 60, OK 22, TN 49, TX 164, VT 3, VA 68, TOTAL = 450 Sanders: AR 12, GA 31, MA 52, OK 19, TN 24, TX 80, VT 23, VA 37, TOTAL = 278 In total, the indicated states have a total of 728 delegates (slightly less than total due to underestimated percentages on 538 forecasts). Thus, Clinton is projected to win 450/728 and Sanders 278/728. Adding in the current delegate count, Clinton is projected to have 541/884=61% and Sanders  343/884=39%. I'm going to extremize since the question is odds of LEADING, not how much of total. I'll double the odds, making it Clinton:Sanders 3.13:1 (from 61:39~=1.56:1), or 76:24 in percentages. This puts Clinton slightly higher than current consensus, which my "gut" says is too low as well. Bernie will need to luck out in multiple states to make a challenge by end of Super Tuesday.

Vermont (16 Delegates): Clinton should clean up here.... Just kidding - Sanders will take at least 80% of the vote.

This, from 538, pretty much sums it up: "What’s worse for Sanders — of the 865 delegates up for grabs Tuesday, 66 percent come from these six [Southern] states. An average of polls in each state gives Clinton at least a 23 percentage point lead in all of them. These include the two biggest prizes of Super Tuesday: Georgia (102 delegates) where Clinton is up by 39 percentage points and Texas (222 delegates) where Clinton is up by 29 percentage points. If the delegates from these states broke perfectly proportionally based on the polling average, Clinton would end up with a 369 to 202 delegate lead. In the other six Super Tuesday contests, Sanders has a clear lead in only Vermont, and the candidates are likely to split the delegates in the other five contests fairly evenly. That means that on Super Tuesday, Clinton is likely to win around 508 delegates and Sanders 357." Know the Power Players and Their Preferences - "This is not to discount randomness. As a general principle though, figuring out which players have the power to win and would benefit the most from a win is not the worst way to make a prediction."  The remaining states that compose the Super Tuesday primaries are heavily favorable to Clinton. Although my personal preferences should be largely disregarded, I maintain a probability that somehow Sanders can garner a momentum boost as he has done in the past leading up to Super Tuesday. However, Hilary is appearing more and more dominant as we approach March 1. Oklahoma, Texas, Arkansas, Virginia, Tennessee, Georgia, and Alabama are essentially a lock for Clinton. If Bernie can somehow take Mass, Colorado, Vermont and maybe take a "lock" or two from Clinton then it's possible, but highly unlikely.

The remaining states to vote before or on Super Tuesday are very favorable for Hillary Clinton. According to recent polls outside of Vermont there are no states where Bernie is a clear favorite, and there are only two other states where he is expected to be competitive (Massachusetts and Oklahoma). With the Democratic delegates being distributed proportionally even if Bernie manages to win both Massachusetts and Oklahoma, he is unlikely to win by large enough margins to gain significantly more delegates then Hillary. With Hillary being so far ahead in the polls in Texas and Georgia which have large numbers of delegates, even if Bernie wins Vermont by a large margin and wins competitive races in Massachusetts and Oklahoma it should not be enough to make up for the delegates Hillary is expected to win in these large states. The only way I could see Bernie coming out ahead after Super Tuesday would be if something drastic happens before Super Tuesday states vote, or if the current polls used to reach this conclusion are drastically inaccurate. Giving each of these scenarios generously a 1% chance of occurring is how I reached my 98%-2% prediction.

Start with Nate Silver's recent analysis of where the race would be if Sanders and Clinton were equal in the polls: http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/bernie-sanderss-path-to-the-nomination/
Here are the states that vote before Super Tuesday combined with Clinton's advantage, assuming equal national polling:
Texas (222 delegates): +20
Georgia (102 delegates): +24
Massachusetts (91 delegates): -11
Virginia (95 delegates): +9
Minnesota (77 delegates): -17
Colorado (66 delegates): -13
Tennessee (67 delegates): +4
Alabama (53 delegates): +27
South Carolina (53 delegates): +11
Nevada (35 delegates): +3
Oklahoma (38 delegates): -2
Arkansas (32 delegates): +20
Vermont (16 delegates): -49 Assume these are right and assume that Clinton's average share of the remaining vote is x. Then Clinton's delegate count is 32 + 222 * ((x+20)/100) + 102 * ((x+24)/100) etc. Unless I've screwed up the numbers it looks like Clinton can get about half the delegates with only 43% of the vote, so Sanders needs an eight-point national lead to be winning. At the moment Clinton has a twelve-point lead in national polls. It does look like Sanders is overperforming in contested states—he is doing five or six points better than a twelve-point Clinton advantage would suggest. But for him to win he would need a further swing of twelve points. That's not exactly impossible. Sanders could have a breakthrough with black or Latino voters, or a little more bad news for Clinton could give him more momentum, etc. But it does seem very very unlikely. My new estimate is 8%.

"Democratic Party rules distinguish pledged and unpledged delegates. Pledged delegates are selected based on their announced preferences in the contest for the presidential nomination. In the party primary elections and caucuses in each U.S. state, voters express their preference among the contenders for the party's nomination for President of the United States. (1) Pledged delegates supporting each candidate are chosen in approximate ratio to their candidate’s share of the vote.  They fall into three categories: district-level pledged delegates (usually by congressional districts); at-large pledged delegates; and pledged PLEO (Party Leaders and Elected Officials) delegates.  (2) In a minority of the states, delegates are legally required to support the candidate to whom they are pledged.  In addition to the states' requirements, the party rules state (Rule 12.J): "Delegates elected to the national convention pledged to a presidential candidate shall in all good conscience reflect the sentiments of those who elected them." By contrast, the  (3) unpledged PLEO delegates (Rule 9.A) are seated without regard to their presidential preferences, solely by virtue of being current or former elected officeholders and party officials. Many of them have chosen to announce endorsements, but they are not bound in any way. They may support any candidate they wish, including one who has dropped out of the presidential race. (4) The other superdelegates, the unpledged add-on delegates  (Rule 9.B), who need not be PLEOs, are selected by the state parties after some of the pledged delegates are chosen, but they resemble the unpledged PLEO delegates in being free to vote as they wish. Unpledged PLEO delegates should not be confused with pledged PLEOs. Under Rule 9.C, the pledged PLEO slots are allocated to candidates based on the results of the primaries and caucuses. Another difference between pledged PLEOs and unpledged PLEOs is that there is a fixed number of pledged PLEO slots for each state, while the number of unpledged PLEOs can change during the campaign.  (5) Pledged PLEO delegates are not generally considered superdelegates."

There are a total of 1,034 pledged delegates by Super Tuesday.  Currently the candidates are essentially tied in delegates (Hillary @ 32, Bernie @ 36).  In the 15 additional contests that will take place by the end of Super Tuesday on March 1 there are 966 pledged delegates available, of which 307 are in explicitly Southern states (five states) with another 317 in Southern-ish Texas (222) and Virginia (95).   So that's a total of 624 (65%) of the remaining-till-Super-Tuesday delegates in Southern-ish states.  The remaining 35% (342 delegates) are in Nevada, American Samoa, Colorado, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Oklahoma, Vermont and Americans abroad.   Hillary is projected to do well in the South, where the Dem electorate is more diverse and her family has political history.  Also, and this is more intangible, but I have a hard time discounting the fact that Southern states seem less likely to vote for someone describing himself as a socialist (democratic or any other variety) than does someone somewhere like Minnesota or living abroad.   Reliable polling is thin for many of these contests right now, but what I am able to find puts Hillary in the neighborhood of 60% support in the Southern-ish states.  Underestimating that slightly, if Hillary gets 55% of the vote it would add 343 delegates from Southern-ish states for a total of 375 to Bernie’s 317.   In the remaining elections, Bernie would need 200 (58.5%) of the remaining delegates to tie.  That is a higher percentage than I am using to estimate Hillary’s support in the Southern-ish states.  While I think Bernie will do better in the non-Southern-ish races, I don’t think those contests will give him enough of a boost to beat Hillary’s strength among the larger Southern-ish delegates.   I’ll revisit this if better polls or aggregations come out (if anyone has those, please share!), or of course if any game changing events happen.   One thing I didn’t account for here is crossover voting in states with open access to vote in either one of the Dem or GOP primaries.  Will try to look at that in the future – Dem participation rates may fall if some Democrats are happy with either candidate and therefore are more interested in affecting the GOP race, which is more interesting every day.  If that occurs, I think it would favor Bernie as his voters are more enthusiastic and therefore more likely to vote in the Dem contest regardless of what happens with the GOP side.
